{"title_page": "Marcello Farabegoli", "text_new": "\n\n{{short description|Italian curator living in Vienna|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n'''Marcello Farabegoli''' (born March 20, 1973 in [[Cesena]]) is an [[Italy|Italian]] [[curator]] living in [[Vienna]]. \n\nMarcello Farabegoli grew up in [[Bolzano-Bozen]]. After completing a master's degree in physics at the [[University of Vienna]] he participated in several environmental and cultural organizations in Berlin. He was also a research assistant at the Physics department at the [[University of Potsdam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uni-potsdam.de/de/physikdidaktik/mitarbeiter.htm|title=Homepage of the University of Potsdam (In German)|publisher=|accessdate=24 February 2018}}</ref>. There he investigated the correlation between physics and aesthetics. Between 2005 - 2010, he ran a gallery for contemporary Japanese art in Berlin <ref>[http://www.faz.net/aktuell/feuilleton/kunstmarkt/galerien/aktuelle-kunst-von-starken-winden-gezeichnet-11027243.html Article by Niklas Maak in] [[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]] (German newspaper), August 16, 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.faz.net/aktuell/feuilleton/kunstmarkt/malerei-der-gegenwart-linientreu-die-japanische-malerin-hana-usui-bei-oko-berlin-1304803.html Article by Niklas Maak in] [[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]] (German newspaper), February 25, 2006</ref>. Since 2010, Farabegoli was based in Vienna and worked in the Old Master Painting department at the [[Dorotheum]] auction house. Since 2013, Farabegoli worked mainly as a freelance curator and producer of art projects. \nIn April 2017, Ambassador Giorgio Marrapodi on behalf of the President of the ltalian Republic, [[Sergio Mattarella]], has awarded Marcello Farabegoli the ltalian distinction of 'Cavaliere dell'Ordine della Stella d'ltalia' (Knight of the [[Order of the Star of Italy]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ambvienna.esteri.it/ambasciata_vienna/de/ambasciata/news/dall-ambasciata/2017/04/conferimento-onorificenze_0.html|title=Verleihung von Ehrenzeichen|website=www.ambvienna.esteri.it|accessdate=24 February 2018}}</ref>\nSources:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.viennavant.at/staff-members/mag-marcello-farabegoli/|title=Mag. Marcello Farabegoli \u2013 viennAvant|website=www.viennavant.at|accessdate=24 February 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://www.salto.bz/de/article/27122016/das-schoene-das-wahre-das-gute Article by Martin Hanni in salto.bz (Italian-German newsportal for] [[South Tyrol|South Tirol]]), December 27, 2016</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://2017.viennaartweek.at/en/journal/rote-raum-linien|title=Red space lines|first=VIENNA ART WEEK|last=2017|website=VIENNA ART WEEK 2017|accessdate=24 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Selected projects == \n* 2019, 150 Years Japan - Austria: ''JAPAN UNLIMITED'', frei_raum Q21 exhibition space [[Museumsquartier | MuseumsQuartier Wien]] with [[Makoto Aida]], [[Chim-Pom |Chim\u2191Pom]], Gianmaria Gava, [[Edgar Honetschl\u00e4ger]], Sachiko Kazama, Jake Knight, BuBu de la Madeleine & [[Yoshiko Shimada]], Midori Mitamura, [[Yoshinori Niwa]], Ryts Monet, Tomoko Sawada, [[Sputniko!]], Ryudai Takano, Shinpei Takeda, Momoyo Torimitsu, [[Hana Usui]], Tomoko Yoneda and Naoko Yoshimoto. Inaugurated by Elisabeth Hajek, Artistic Director frei_raum Q21 exhibition space / MQ, Marcus Bergmann, Ambassador and Deputy Head of Section V for External Cultural Relations of the Austrian Ministry for Europe, Integration and Foreign Affairs (BMEIA), Diethard Leopold, President of the Austrian-Japanese Society, and Marcello Farabegoli, curator of the exhibition. Side events with Judith Brandner ([[ORF]]), Lucas Gehrmann ([[Kunsthalle Wien]]), Felicitas Thun-Hohenstein ([[Academy of Fine Arts Vienna]]  & [[Austrian pavilion]] Venice Biennale), Niklass Maak ([[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung | FAZ]]), Diethard Leopold (\u00d6JG), [[Bernhard Scheid]] ([[Austrian Academy of Sciences]]), Gerorg Schneider (Japannual), [[Monika Sommer]] (Haus der Geschichte \u00d6sterreich), Markus Wurzer ([[University of Graz]]) and others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mqw.at/en/institutions/q21/frei-raum-q21-exhibition-space/2019/japan-unlimited/|title=Japan Unlimited|website=www.mqw.at|accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mqw.at/en/institutions/q21/program/2019/09/event-programme-as-part-of-the-exhibition-japan-unlimited/|title=Japan Unlimited - side events|website=www.mqw.at|accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marcello-farabegoli.net/japan-unlimited/|title=Japan Unlimited|website=www.marcello-farabegoli.net|accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.e-flux.com/announcements/249825/japan-unlimited/|title=Press release Japan Unlimited. September 17, 2019|website=www.e-flux.com|url-status=dead}}{{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://moussemagazine.it/japan-unlimited-frei_raum-q21-museumsquartier-wien-vienna-2019/|title=Japan Unlimited|website=www.moussemagazine.it|accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2019/11/06/national/vienna-art-exhibition-fukushima-wwii/#.Xodap25uLIU|title=Japan Embassy pulls backing for Vienna exhibition with works about Fukushima No. 1 and WWII. November 6, 2019|website=www.japantimes.co.jp}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20191121/p2a/00m/0et/023000c|title='Freedom of expression': Austrian art display blasts Japan gov't for ending support. November 21, 2019|website=www.mainichi.jp}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/japanese-embassy-objects-vienna-show-1697463|title=The Japanese Embassy in Austria Has Withdrawn Support for a Show That Includes Controversial Japanese Artists. November 6, 2019|website=www.artnet.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://apps.derstandard.at/privacywall/story/2000110847491/kritische-kunst-ueber-japan-japanik-um-wiener-ausstellung|title=Kritische Kunst \u00fcber Japan: Japanik um Wiener Ausstellung. 9. November 2019|website=www.derstandard.at}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.artribune.com/dal-mondo/2019/11/mostra-japan-unlimited-vienna/|title=Japan Unlimited. Giappone vs Austria per \u201ccolpa\u201d di una mostra. 9 Novembre 2019|website=www.artribune.com}}</ref>\n* 2017, special project of the Vienna Art Week at ARCC.art open space: exhibition ''Carmine'' by Ben G. Fodor and round table about Art & Science with [[Georg Gottlob]], professor of informatics at Oxford University & TU-Vienna, Gerfried Stocker, artistic director of [[Ars Electronica]], Ben G. Fodor, artist, and Marcello Farabegoli, curator of the exhibition / moderated by Dorothee Frank, journalist at [[\u00d61]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://2017.viennaartweek.at/en/program/ausstellung-ben-g-fodor-carmine|title=Exhibition: Ben G. Fodor, \u00bbCarmine\u00ab|first=VIENNA ART WEEK|last=2017|website=VIENNA ART WEEK 2017|accessdate=24 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marcello-farabegoli.net/carmine.html|title=Carmine|website=www.marcello-farabegoli.net|accessdate=24 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artmagazine.cc/content100479.html|title=Ben G. Fodor - Carmine: Rote Liniengef\u00fcge auf Schwarz|website=www.artmagazine.cc|accessdate=24 February 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://www.salto.bz/de/article/29112017/kunst-auf-der-parabolischen-bahn Article by Martina Genetti in salto.bz (Italian-German newsportal for] [[South Tyrol|South Tirol]]), November 30, 2017</ref>\n* 2017, section project statements of the Parallel Vienna: ''Parallel & concordant'' with Ben G. Fodor & Dorothee Frank, Clemens F\u00fcrtler & Michaela Seiser, Inge GRAF & Walter ZYX, Karin Pliem & Lucas Gehrmann, Eva Schlegel & Carl Pruscha, Rudi Stanzel & Andrea Schurian, Viktoria Tremmel & Kurt Kladler, [[Hana Usui]] & Marcello Farabegoli; Curated and produced by Marcello Farabegoli and Lucas Gehrmann.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marcello-farabegoli.net/parallel2017.html|title=parallel2017|website=www.marcello-farabegoli.net|acce